@node "Intr" "Introduction"

                                @{b}@{fg shine}Introduction@{fg text}@{ub}

CyberClock is a nice digital clock for WB. I made it because I @{b}hate@{ub} analog
clocks, and there is a whole lot of them, each prettier then the other. I
simply can't understand why would someone want to use such inaccurate method
of time displaying on a computer. And so I have tried to make digital clock
which would also be beautiful.

The only program with similar features I know of is TinyMeter, but it's much
more then just a clock, eats a lot of memory (not tiny at all!) and can only
use fonts for it's digits.

CyberClock uses IFF brushes for it's digits, leaving their look only to your
imagination. I gave my best to make it as small as possible (for example,
iff.library is used only when a picture is loading, and it could be flushed
from memory after CyberClock is started) and to use little CPU time (six
times less then original Amiga clock). I think you'll enjoy it!

@endnode
@node "Inst" "Installation"

                                @{b}@{fg shine}Installation@{fg text}@{ub}

@{fg shine}Automatic:@{fg text}

Double click on @{b}Install CyberClock@{ub} icon, then follow the instructions.
See a note about @{"ReInstallation" link "ReIn"}.

@{fg shine}Manual:@{fg text}

Copy CyberClock#?                  @{fg shine}to@{fg text} SYS:WBStartup
Copy CyberClock.guide#?            @{fg shine}to@{fg text} wherewer:you/want
Copy libs/iff.library              @{fg shine}to@{fg text} LIBS:
Copy libs/screennotify.library     @{fg shine}to@{fg text} LIBS:
Copy Digits/CyberClock_desired.bsh @{fg shine}to@{fg text} S:CyberClock.bsh

@endnode
@node "Usag" "Usage"

                                    @{b}@{fg shine}Usage@{fg text}@{ub}

@{fg shine}Starting from Workbench:@{fg text}

Doubleclick on icon.

Following tooltypes are supported:

@{b}CONFIG@{ub}

Configuration file CyberClock will use. Defaults to S:CyberClock.prefs

@{b}DIGITS@{ub}

IFF brush with digits CyberClock will use. Defaults to S:CyberClock.bsh

@{fg shine}Starting from CLI:@{fg text}

Type @{b}CyberClock@{ub} in CLI prompt.

Following arguments are recognised (in that order):

@{b}CONFIG@{ub}

Configuration file CyberClock will use. Defaults to S:CyberClock.prefs

@{b}DIGITS@{ub}

IFF brush with digits CyberClock will use. Defaults to S:CyberClock.bsh

@{fg shine}Menus:@{fg text}

@{b}Project@{ub}

  @{b}About@{ub}

  Displays information about CyberClock.

  @{b}Quit@{ub}

  Exits CyberClock. Without warning.

@{b}Settings@{ub}

  @{b}Stay front@{ub}

  If this is on, CyberClock will bring it's window in front of all other
  windows every second. If this is off, it'll behave normally.

  @{b}Time format@{ub}

    @{b}24h@{ub}

    If this is on, time will be displayed in 24 hours format.

    @{b}12h@{ub}

    If this is on, time will be displayed in 12 hours format (but not with
    AM/PM).

    @{b}HH:MM:SS@{ub}

    If this is on, time will be displayed with seconds.

    @{b}HH:MM@{ub}

    If this is on, time will be displayed without seconds. NOTE: CPU usage
    won't become lower.

  @{b}Lock window@{ub}

  If this is on, window will be locked on screen and couldn't be moved.

  @{b}Save Settings@{ub}

  Saves your settings to config file with which CyberClock is started. It
  will save status of @{b}Settings@{ub} menu items and window position.

@endnode
@node "Digi" "Digits brush"

                               @{b}@{fg shine}Digits brushes@{fg text}@{ub}

Digits brushes are normal IFF ILBM brushes which contain digits CyberClock
can use. If you want to make one, simply go to your favourite paint program,
and draw or type in digits of desired look, in order of @{fg shine}0123456789:@{fg text} . All
digits must have exactly the same width. When that is done, simply cut away
the brush, making sure that it's width is not less then 11 times digit width,
and save it to disk. See @{"Usage" link "Usag"} for information on how to tell CyberClock to
use digits brush with name different then default.

CyberClock always uses Workbench colors for digits representation. So,
regardless of which palette your brush actually has, color 0 on brush becomes
color 0 on Workbench, color 1 on brush becomes color 1 on Workbench, etc.
This is also the answer to everyone who wants to change the background color.

If you think that you've drawn a nice digits brush and if you want to share
it with others, send it to the @{"author" link "Auth"}, and if he thinks the same, it'll
appear in next release of CyberClock.
@endnode
@node "Regs" "Registration"

                                @{b}@{fg shine}Registration@{fg text}@{ub}

CyberClock is an emailware program, which means that, if you are using it
regurarely, you should send an email to it's @{"author" link "Auth"} saying that you want to
register. Because I would realy like to see how many people are using it and
where it is used, I decided to boost your feedback a bit by adding annnoying
requester on start of CyberClock. It can be closed only three seconds after
it is opened, so that I think that it isn't @{b}realy@{ub} annoying.

If you want that requester to be removed, and CyberClock to start normaly,
and also your name to appear in About requester and this guide, send an email
to @{"me" link "Auth"} (@{fg fill}@{u}@{"smolensk@eunet.yu" system "C:OpenURL mailto:smolensk@eunet.yu"}@{uu}@{fg text}) saying that you want to register CyberClock and to
which name you want it to be registered. You will probably want to attach
your configuration file (configuration file is keyfile at the same time) to
email (NOTE: if you are using YAM, UUEncode it, @{b}don't@{ub} Base64 encode it), so
that you won't loose your configuration. If you don't have an email, you can
send @{"me" link "Auth"} a letter with empty (or full :) 3.5" disk, envelope and IRC, and I'll
send you back keyfile on the disk.

If you have time, you can also fill out the following form:

@{fg shine}---8<--- cut here ---8<-----------------------------------------------------@{fg text}
Hello,

I'm from _______________ in _______________

I have Amiga _____ OS version _._, ___MB RAM, ____MB HD, 680_0 CPU, equipped
